I would look first at the average number of pickups at each district. Then, I would look at the average amount of drivers going to the one district that had the highest percentage of pickups. I would then decide based on those two diameters which district I would choose for each round. However, I changed tactics on some rounds based on the fact that sometimes choosing the same district in multiple rounds lead to no pickup, so I would adjust to the district with the second highest average of pickups in those cases.

I actually went with the district that had the lowest probability of pickup. I knew that 60% of drivers would look at the same display as I would, and likely would go to the district with the highest probability. They falsely believed that they were the only ones looking at the display, whereas in reality, everybody could see the same display. That meant that a lot of drivers would falsely think that they were making the right decision of going to the same district as a bunch of other drivers, thereby actually lowering the district's probability by the time they got there. I went with the lowest probability since that meant less drivers would go there, ironically. In addition, the probabilities were actually based off of past driver experiences. So even if 40% of the drivers wouldn't use the display, they would still be relying on the same type of information, and they too would end up going to the same districts at the same time.
I went to the district that indicated the lowest pick up rate because I knew that other drivers would likely seek out areas with higher pick up rates.
